: after My Last Days aired, i realized the power representationally in sharing my story for the chronically/terminally ill community. it’s also important for the students i teach to not just see my highlights, but to see there are pits amongst those insanely special moments. it’s vital for their mental health to see someone that can live through, struggle, & sometimes even thrive through the deepest of valleys. 

a lot has gone on medically for me in 2022. most i’ve chosen not to share publicly as it’s been a lot to download. the energy it takes sometimes to help others process deeply complicated medical situations sometimes depletes my own supply. most people are conditioned to comprehend singular battles. there’s less capacity for chronic, lifelong ones. it’s hard to balance what to share & what to keep close, so thank you for your grace as i grapple with it all. 

if you want to read a lil about my current situation, scroll. but first, i gently remind everyone of this.

- a lot of people are fighting battles you know nothing about ; be kind.
- you may think you know 100% of someone’s story, but sometimes you know 100% of 10%. you don’t have to know the other 90% to be kind. 
- please consider your words before making suggestions to the chronically ill. most of us have gone to the corners of the world with our money, resources, energy & time. there is rarely an avenue western or alternative that hasn’t been explored. while intention is usually pure, suggestions often feel like a drastic oversimplification of an issue that is more complex than you can begin to imagine. 
- joy is not mutually exclusive to health. you don’t have to be physically healed to have & deserve moments of happiness, accomplishment & wonderment. one of my biggest dreams came true last week in the midst of this. to the newly diagnosed or those in the thick of it, i promise you will experience joy more deeply due to the depths of your perspective.
- you are the sky & your feelings are the weather. nothing is permanent except for you. weather comes & goes, sometimes waxing, other times waning. no feeling no matter how hopeless & encompassing will last forever. please stay.

#chronicillness

it had never once crossed my mind that i might meet @therealkmckidd. why ? because he’s that good at his job. so good in fact that my brain could not process him as anyone but Owen Hunt when meeting him. Owen Hunt exists in Seattle at Grey Sloan Memorial pulling icicles out of peoples’ chests NOT at Staples Center without Teddy. 

seeing him out of character rocked me so hard, when introduced, all my many words about Grey’s were reduced to babble. so Kevin, if you happen to read this, this is what i meant to say.

thank you for committing so much of your career to a show that means so much to so many of us. thank you for being so phenomenal in your role that my brain literally could not comprehend you as anyone else.

thank you for portraying such a complex, multi dimensional character, who is both extraordinarily heroic and deeply flawed. and for bringing such immense humanity to a character who has both survived and even thrived through so much trauma and PTSD. 

some claim the show unbelievable, but for me, it’s the closest depiction of what is and has always been my reality. Grey’s Anatomy is where i recognize myself and my world most on a television screen. thank you for making me and a lot of us a little less lonely.

: when i was diagnosed with Vascular Ehlers Danlos, i was told i wouldn’t make it to my 4th decade. so to make it to the last year in a decade i was predicted to not make it through feels like a major win. to grow older is a blessing many don’t get to have. 39 is an honor. giving everyone ample warning now - when i make it to 40 next year, we’re throwing the party of the century. 🎉 

thank you from the bottom of my heart for all the birthday love. through my own choice, i have sacrificed so much normalcy to live an unconventional artistic life. i don’t have kids of my own, but much of my life has been spent pouring into generations of other peoples’ kids & young adults. as one gets older, to not have the status quo of what so many my age have, can at times feel alienating. yesterday i was inundated with hundreds of beautiful messages from so many, but largely from over 2 decades of students. it reminded me of a Chelsea Handler podcast when she said something to the effect of - it’s a parent’s job to love their kid the most, but someone has to love ALL the kids the most. adult or child, big or small - i’m humbly grateful to have even been a small piece of your journey. 

38 was not easy. it was a year of integrating tremendous grief & loss into my every day. it was a year of fighting constant medical battles ; a high price to pay for surviving a decade most don’t. but it was a year of tremendous personal growth. i have more clarity than i’ve ever had in my life because my vision is not clouded by fear. home is no longer in other people, but in me. whoever walks in or out, i know i will always be okay, because i’ve got me. & she’s strong AF and has occasionally been known to bend the universe to her will. 🪐 the magic is in me ; just like it’s in all of you. 💫 

so here’s to another year of art, life & finding the roses amongst all the thorns. the roses aren’t always in bloom, but when they are, they smell like they’ve been dropped off by God. 🌹 

see you this time next year. probably a little more battered & bruised, but in a great pair of shoes crossing the finish line to 40. you all know it’s my fav pastime to do something someone said i couldn’t. 💜

: i thought a long time about how to approach this song as there seemed to be this beautiful purposeful confusion & overlap if @lauramvula was speaking about her actual father or God. i love that she leaves it up to the audience & we certainly mirrored a bit of that grey in our interpretation as well. 

faith/spirituality/religion is an interesting, personal topic for all & something i’m always wrestling with myself. when i began to reflect about what my actual relationship with God had been, my soul spit out this piece. twisty, turbulent, unsettled, sometimes angry, sometimes harmonious, & at times, seemingly evasive on both ends. but what came to me again & again was how often in my life i have heedlessly climbed to the highest of heights jumping with full confidence & a deep inner knowing that a net will appear. and isn’t that the very definition of faith ? believing in something for which there is no evidence ? ✨

this is a clip of a quick turn around video submission i was asked to turn in following an in person submission. it’s interesting, when you get to a certain level, people stop talking about rejection. it’s cooler to maintain the illusion of “i always get it.” but the higher you climb, the harder it gets, bc the thinner the air. everyone in this industry no matter what they’re letting on, is experiencing rejection on one level or another. while heartbreakingly close, this particular dream for this piece didn’t come true, but you know what ? other dreams have since. & i think this piece took on a different dream than what it was originally intended for. this crazy industry of ours is a lot like the concept of faith. artists walk forward pouring endless resources into creating our art & having tremendous belief in something for which there isn’t always a lot of evidence. but if you have faith, another dream might be just around the corner. ✨

: sending love to the cast of @millionlittlethingsabc as their last episode aires tonight - but sending extra, extra love to the brilliant creator, @heydjnash and of course “Maggie”, the ever so talented, @allisonemiller. 

“My Last Days” & @millionlittlethingsabc received a @televisionacad Emmy Honor the same year. that in itself was wild because as i went through chemo that year, i also religiously watched “Maggie” go through chemo, and it was one of the few experiences that brought me comfort and sanity at that time. while you can find many a “sick girl” character on TV, you can’t find one our age, with a full time career, still brimming with hope, life, relationships, and dreams. Maggie was layered and anything but reducted to being the typical one dimensional “sick girl.” to witness @heydjnash develop so much meat and depth in that character, was inspiring as a creator, storyteller, and survivor.

fate somehow aligns that night, and Allison and i end up next to each other on the press line. i get to find out that she’s as good of a person as she is an actress. we formed an instant bond that’s still present today. 

i approach DJ at the end of the night and before i can say who i am he grabs me in a huge hug and says, “Can I get a selfie with you ?” my face in the second slide deserves an Emmy in itself for playing it cool. humility and kindness radiated out of him. we spoke for a long time that night and at the end he said, “I’ll never forget you. I will always take you with me when I write for Maggie.” i don’t know if that’s true, but i do know that DJ has carried many people with him in writing for this show’s rich characters, and i’m awfully proud to be one little millionth of the lives he’s impacted.

: "have you ever really had a teacher ? one who saw you as a raw but precious thing. a jewel that, with wisdom, could be polished to a proud shine ? if you are lucky enough to find your way to such teachers, you will always find your way back home.” - mitch albom.

what i’m most passionate about in this life will always be dance education. my dance teachers saved my life, in many cases acted as parental figures, and were often the most permanent, stable fixtures in my life. i hung on their every word, so much so that as a kid, i had a journal i wrote everything they ever said to me down. i took their word as impervious ; it was gold. i would have followed them to the ends of the Earth. which is why, i feel so protective of the platform. when i’m standing on that stage, mic in hand, and i see those eager faces looking up at me, i know i was once one of them. which is why i don’t have a lot of tolerance for those who abuse the power of the platform.

some of my teachers were unyieldingly tough, some set expectations higher than what i thought i could reach, some were more nurturing, exuding a quiet belief. many made me part of their families, raising me as their own, and some kept me at arm’s length. most made mistakes, as anyone does trying really hard at something. but all watered me as an artist and a human in their own unique way. i am forever grateful and will spend my lifetime making sure you all know and feel it.

i hope that of all the qualities i try to instill in the many dancers who have passed through me over the last 21 years, it is gratitude. gratitude for those who invested in you. it’s important to remember where you came from because it’s the easiest way to locate where you are. when you have an anchor you can withstand any storm. flying is not the same thing as pushing away from the ground. 

many thanks to my teachers, mentors, and in many cases second moms pictured here and not pictured. happy dance teacher appreciation day ! thanks for loving me through every season, even the most stubborn ones. 💜

: today i go #REDS4VEDS for Vascular Ehlers Danlos Day. vEDS is an incurable GENETIC connective tissue disorder. vEDS is particularly serious because of the risk for spontaneous arterial or organ rupture. vEDS is est to occur to 1 in 200,000 & results from pathogenic variants in COL3A1, which are responsible for producing chains of procollagen, a major protein in the walls of blood vessels & hollow organs. vEDS alters the framework used to build connective tissue, which decreases its capacity to withstand stress. potential fatal effects include arterial aneurysm, dissection, bowel rupture & rupture of the uterus. life span is deeply impacted. 

i wear red today in memory of all the beautiful people we have lost to vEDS & to remind the medical community that occasionally hoof beats ARE in fact zebras not horses. 🦓 i wear red today in hopes that i’ll 1 day never have to explain vEDS to another surgeon that holds my life in their hands. i wear red today hoping that another little girl will not have to go 31 yrs of her life with debilitating symptoms since birth, only to be told to “see a psychiatrist” because so many male physicians had too big of an ego to say, “i don’t know, but let’s find someone who does.”

to my fellow zebras, if you’re exhausted, rest. if you’re drowning in well intended peoples opinions, close your eyes & find the only voice that matters ; your own. if you’re depressed or anxious because of your illness, it’s symptoms, it’s medications, or mistreatment from a broken medical system, it’s valid. admission of this does not invalidate your illness. if you’re overwhelmed by an untreatable, chronic, life long disease & all that it entails, you’ve every right to be. remember that your illness is a part of you but does not define you. you’re allowed to have and fight for a multi dimensional, non marginalized, successful career, meaningful friendships, a beautiful love story & an extraordinary life. 

anyone can slay a dragon, but to wake up every morning loving the world again, knowing the dragon still awaits you, that’s what takes a real hero. 

#VEDS #medicalzebra #REDS4VEDS

: this is going to sound like blasphemy for some of you, but for some reason “Eleanor Rigby” never hit for me until i heard @codyfry’s cover. i’m of course a Beatles fan, but something about Cody’s orchestration colliding with the perspective i currently sit at in my own life, made it resonate especially deep. from first listen of this cover, the song ceased from being “Eleanor Rigby” and immediately became “All the Lonely People.” i spent a good 2 years of Covid analyzing the lyrics off and on, and then spent a couple sleepless nights in @stacey23_spence’s basement (it’s a very nice basement) trying to figure out how to best translate these characters and metaphors to a competition stage. 

we had 2 days to get this right and i’m proud of it, but i’m mostly proud of the kids. from moment one they were ALL IN with ALL their trust and then some. that’s something that makes @dancersburlingtonofficial extraordinary. they dive in with everything they have to any wild idea you’ve got brewing. they are nothing but a joy. congrats to the dancers that worked so hard to make this what it is and the DB fam for investing so much into it. i could list all the amazing awards but i won’t because i want you to understand that the success is not in the trophies but in the text messages i get every weekend from grown adults watching this piece for the first time. you’ve captured a song’s true narrative of loneliness and executed it in a way that resonates with so many far beyond your age. you have done your job as an artist for art is not what you see, it is what you make others see. 

i love you and am v proud of you ALL. 💜

: this month always takes me back to this time in my life. they were the first same sex couple dancing on TV and this episode was the first same sex kiss in a dance show on TV. we fought hard for something that hadn’t crossed my mind that we were going to have to fight for and i’m forever grateful to @nbc & @nbcworldofdance for understanding the importance of this to air. 

i’ve never really spoken about it, but amongst the hundreds of thousands of beautiful messages we received from people who were experiencing representation for the first time, there were death threats raging with hatred sprinkled in as well. i remember thinking, “it’ll get better, it’s just because we were the first.” and now i sit here 5 years later and think, “it hasn’t gotten better, it’s actually gotten so much worse.” i’m unsure we’d be able to air this kiss on prime time safely in 2023. 

representation matters because every person deserves to see themselves reflected in the world around them. when we embrace diversity in all its forms, we create a more inclusive and accepting society. let’s continue to uplift voices that have long been silenced. love is love, and it deserves to be celebrated and recognized in all its embodiments. as we continue to fight for equality and representation for the LGBTQIA+ community, let’s remember that every person deserves to live their life authentically and without fear. 

art is always what drives acceptance and freedom. so artists, please keep telling stories because art matters, art makes history, art pushes tolerance, and love always wins. #pridemonth #pride🌈

: going through a box in my childhood bedroom & found these. Ms. MJ sanctioned consequences from the 90’s. 😊😳😂

I will connect my passé everytime I turn.

Perfection is not possible because dance is an art form.

Rolling my eyes is disrespectful even if it’s because I’m frustrated with myself.

I will use my stubbornness to overcome adversity not towards breaking rules that protect me.

a few things come to mind. 

*effectiveness. all of these sentences are permanently embedded into my brain. there was only 1 i didn’t remember, but then realized i subconsciously repeated the sentence verbatim to a perfectionist in 1 of my classes last week. 

*the 1st time i turned one of these in, i vividly remember her taking the briefest, half a second glance at my work & immediately handing it back to me without even looking up from what she was doing. she didn’t even turn the pages to check that i had actually completed it ! my jaw dropped. sensing my reaction she said, “your lesson, not mine, Marin.” even at that age, my jaw fell another inch at the power & truth of that statement. complete mic drop. 🎤 i don’t remember a time that she ever glanced past the 1st page of these & i don’t remember taking advantage of that because, “it was my lesson not hers.”

*many of these address my battle with perfectionism which stemmed from something far darker. while she never let me lean on any excuse, she knew my heart well enough to know that any behavior that was out of character was tied to something deeper. for a kid that was going through so much that went largely unseen & unspoken, this recognition even if not totally discernible at the time, was lifesaving.

*gratitude. to have lived through a time & place where this could occur & having a dance teacher that loved me so much as her own that she made sure the baggage i carried didn’t outweigh my character, is a priceless gift not many are afforded or willing to receive. 

*finally, it strikes me that she actually may have been teaching me to manifest as many of these sentences seem like positive affirmations. it was discipline, but my heart always knew it was love. 

god bless our dance teachers ; truly unsung heroes. 💜

Marinda Davis (@marinspirations) is a true multi hyphenate #artist. Originally from Florida, Marinda’s #dance training began at the young age of two. Between her training at Mary Jo’s Performing Arts Academy, Blake High School of the Arts, and regional musical theater, it was during these pivotal years that Davis’ signature style gained its eclectic roots. Touring with conventions from age 15, it was on the circuit that Davis began to spread her wings working as assistant to Gus Giordano, Frank Hatchett, Ray Leeper, Dennis Caspary, & Lisa Allain. At 18, Marinda moved to NY to attend Marymount Manhattan College where she obtained a BA in Dance with a Musical Theater minor. Simultaneously, she trained extensively at BDC studying with her mentor, Sheila Barker. Marinda danced professionally with Sting, 98 Degrees, & was a founding & principal dancer for Anthony Morigerato’s, AMDP, NY.

Marinda is the Artistic Director of her company, #marInspired ; the storytellers, founded in 2009. In 2012, she premiered marInspired’s first full length NY show, “Breakable” enjoying a sold out run at Salvatore Capezio Theater. This same year, Marinda received her 1st #Capezio ACEAward nomination. Now based in LA, Marinda was nominated for her 2nd Capezio #ACEAward in 2015 & received 2nd place & funding for “UNbreakable”, the company’s 2nd full-length show. They previewed at #Dancerpalooza and premiered their big full show at the El Portal in Hollywood in 2016. In January of 2017, Marinda produced “UNbreakable” at NY’s Symphony Space.

She continues to guide countless artists to and through their professional careers as a faculty member for #PaceUniversity Commercial Dance and remains a beacon of light to the industry through her #choreography, classes, public speaking engagements, and writings.

: Ms. Tammi was my childhood dance teacher. She loved me even when I was an awkward caterpillar, long before there were any signs of sprouting wings. It’s easy as a dance teacher to love a talented kid, but she loved me far before talent showed it’s head. 🐛 

Ms. Tam always made it very clear to me that who I was as a person was more valued than how good I was at dance. Fall out of a turn ? Forgivable. But a yes without a “ma’am”, a request without a “please”, an even slightly disrespectful tone of voice, profanity, a bad grade, lack of gratitude, an eye roll, a poor work ethic, an absence of graciousness, or even a hint of unkindness witnessed toward another, absolutely unacceptable. It’s difficult to measure exactly how deeply this impacted my life in such early, formative years, but all these years later, she flows through & out of me more & more with every passing day. 🌊 

When I think what lesson of hers was most impactful, I think of this one. When I was 14, I was the only one who got in trouble for something many did. I’d definitely found my voice at this point & when I expressed how unfair this was she posed a question. “Care or not care ?” She went on to explain that if she was going to invest in me, I didn’t get to pick when. That caring didn’t mean only praise, but it also meant accountability & consequence, which was also love. To whom much is given, much is required. So she made me choose that day - have a status quo teacher/student relationship or have someone deeply invest in me even if that came with some taxes I didn’t necessarily want to pay. I pouted my way through it, but in 1997 I picked care & never turned back. 

This reframe of love for me at such a young age sent me onward to seek out life altering truthful mentors who would also care on this level ; propelling me forward, ultimately ensuring my reputation & integrity in a tough & largely egocentric industry. I am forever grateful to my first second mom. 🙏🏻

Happy Birthday to the safest, most nurturing soul with the kindest heart. I don’t know a better human on this Earth, @tammigodinez. You deserve the world. The softest parts of me will always be you. Love, Your Butterfly 🦋

: Happy Birthday to my mentor & mama, @sheilabarker629. A BIG congratulations is also in order as last night she was recognized by @danceteachermagazine as a 2023 Dance Teacher Award Recipient. To witness her in this much deserved moment of glory was very special indeed.

In thinking of what story to share today, this one feels in alignment. By 2007, I had been training with her 6 days a week at @bdcnyc and Marymount for six years. I said something to her one day like, “I want to dance for you for the rest of my life.” She pointed to the interim BDC door and said, “Get out, it’s time to go. You’re too good to be a professional class taker. I’ve taught you everything I know. You’ve got to go.” I nervously laughed and she doubled down in volume & intensity, “Go and don’t ever come back. I don’t want to see you again.” 

I cried for months. My abandonment wound and my age couldn’t hear the immense love between the words. 

Five long years later she sat front and center at @marinspired’s first full length show. She brought flowers (slide 4) and when she handed them to me she said, “This level of talent is why I told you to go. You’re too loyal and stubborn to have left without force. I had to hurt you that deeply for you to fly & realize your genius.” 

I reflect on that story at my age now and see such selflessness in that act. I was her right hand at the time. To love & believe in someone so much that you’re willing to inconvenience yourself & kick them out of the nest knowing with confidence I’d find my wings on the way down because of her raising & training, is self sacrifice and generosity at it’s finest. A great educator adapts to what each student requires & responds to, and she knew my heart well enough to know, if she didn’t get me out of there then, I’d still be there to this day. 

“Most people don’t know there are angels whose only job is to make sure you don’t get too comfortable & miss your life.”

Happy Birthday to my anchor from your storm - to my Bailey from your Meredith. You were wrong about one thing, I’ll never stop learning from you. 💜⚓️

: happy birthday to my bff @tommytoes7 ! i’ll always remember that fateful sunday in @shishibarker’s class in 2005. she pulled us up to lead warm up & 2 mins in we looked at each other through the mirror & nodded in acknowledgement at our identical states of being completely drenched in sweat. when she pulled us out to do the combo together, i remember thinking midway, “you have met your match.” i could feel the vibration of our married energy simmering, just waiting to explode. i kept thinking, “this is dangerous, in the best way possible.”

if you hadn’t of lived our life with me, i don’t think i’d believe it. we’d dance all day professionally, take 3 classes, teach all night, & then run HK until dawn, taking over every dance floor, dancing and i mean DANCING until we nearly dropped. you’d carry me piggy back up & down 9th avenue from one spot to the next like a damn super hero to save my feet from the 6 inch heels i was never not in. we’d leave drenched at last call, refuel at Renaissance diner, watch as the city woke up, go home, catch a couple hours of sleep, & then do it again the next day & the day after without ever missing a beat. it was wild, it was everything, & i believe it is what keeps me sane in the state my body exists in now. it keeps me sane because i know we used every drop God gave us. & while we may not have the same physical ability & energy level now, i know we’re still as full out as ever in ways that truly count.

thanks for living so hard with me, dancing so hard with me, & loving so hard with me. thanks for understanding my crazy, complicated life & always accepting who/what i love. thanks for patiently waiting for me when i stop to talk to every dog & horse on every street. thanks for never once fleeing the scene when i’m being chewed out by Sheila. thanks for capturing every magical moment with McDream. thanks for every Halloween. thank you for being you. i love you so, so much & am so grateful for you. to see your many gifts & talents deservedly appreciated & celebrated is the best thing ever. to another year of being too much, to your NEW year of crystal clear vision, & to an autumn of us getting to share our city again. 💜

I’m a long time, die hard @ingridmichaelson fan and I’d been holding onto this one for awhile. Like any Ingrid OG, I first heard this 16 years ago on the @greysabc Season 3 finale. It’s been my mantra anytime I am stuck in a dire medical situation I cannot control. When I couldn’t walk, I just kept breathing. When I was on the bathroom floor, endlessly puking from chemo, I just kept breathing. I just focus on one breath at a time and find the power in the control of that until breaths become steps, and steps become runs. I guess in a sense this song has always lived in the medical realm for me & while it reflects numerous narratives beyond that space, I wanted to specifically dedicate this to the medical community that heroically worked through Covid. The lives they saved, the lives they tried to save - isolated from their families, exhausted and overworked ; with little time to process or grieve. : whenever i have to get brutally honest with someone i always say, “hold on, because i’m about to be your Robin Dawn.” whatever comes out of my mouth next is usually something that hurts them to hear but comes from the epitome of love. i don’t do it often because it’s that hard. it’s far easier to say the things someone wants to hear, people like you a lot better that way. the love it takes to speak the truth in order to get someone out of their own way - is of tremendous proportion. she’s willing to be that person every single time. her love for you always outweighs her need to be liked.

i tell this story of our origin every year, it’s just too good to not. 16 yrs ago, i got a voicemail from @robinry asking me to teach at her intensive, so i got on a plane. at the end of my class, she dragged me by my elbow into her office. her signature blue acrylic an inch from my face, she said, “You’re incredible. I’ve brought every choreographer into my studio, I know talent when I see it. Everything you’re dreaming about in that brilliant mind of yours is going to come true. But what makes you extra rare is your humility, gratitude & your heart. So if you ever forget where you came from, if I ever find you ungrateful or unkind, no matter your level of success or age, I will (insert 7 second censor bleep & use your most colorful imagination.)” i nervously laughed & the nail flew back at me, “You think I’m kidding ? I don’t make empty threats. Your heart’s what makes you special. I won’t let what will eventually be your success effect that beautiful soul.” i’d formally known this woman for 2 hours. 🤣 

proud to have made it 16 yrs without her having to follow through on that specific infraction. others things, i haven’t learned as quickly. 😅

Mama Robs, i’m thankful for your bark & your bite. extra grateful that you generally bark more than you bite. but the most appreciative that i get to experience the ocean of infinite love beneath that tough exterior.

happy b’day to one of my fav people on this planet who keeps it the realest & never misses a thing. i love you beyond words & am so thankful that a legend like you exists. thanks for truly loving me like i’m yours. 💜

: Two years ago on a plane somewhere over Missouri, my entire world imploded. While I have a high tolerance for trauma, nothing prepared me for the avalanche of losing Serge. Some days, I feel like I’m still on that plane. In shock, in need of sedation, demanding that they turn that plane around to NY so I can personally verify news my heart literally could not and sometimes still can’t process. 

Time. People always say time. The thing is, time doesn’t permit you to get over a loss, but instead it allows you the space to learn how to move with it - even dance with it. You must shake hands with your grief & welcome her in, for she lives with you now. Pull her a chair to your table and offer her comfort. For she is not the monster you first thought her to be - she is love. And she will walk with you now, stay with you now, if you let her. And on the days when your anger is high, remember why she came, remember who she represents. Remember - grief came to you, because love came first. LOVE CAME FIRST.

Wherever I am, you’re there too. 

Will never leave. 

I love you, Sergey Alexander Onik.

: took my first class from @suzitaylor30 when i was 11 and instantly fell head over heels. i remember looking up at her on that big stage and willing my future to look like hers. she was powerful, kind, quietly tough, talented, and above all, she felt like absolute magic. 🪄 

my adoration of her as a kid ran famously deep. i permed my hair for 3 years to look like her and when she called me her “lyrical doll” it became my (really dating myself here) AOL screen name. she gave the best hugs and always made me feel seen, celebrated, and safe ; the last being something i desperately needed at the time.

years later, during my first semester as a freshman at Marymount, 3 days in, i had to withdraw from dance classes due to a medical problem. i was heartbroken. to move 2000 miles away not knowing a soul to pursue your dreams, and then have that snatched away was devastating. i remember aimlessly wandering the city to Steps to find Suzi. she let me cry, got me back up on my feet, and helped me make a schedule. everything was okay again because i got to train with her that semester. and everything was okay because Suzi is like a golden compass - she was home. 💫 

believe it or not, we would not see each other again in person for another 20 years. we were finally reunited this September at Pace. 11 year old Marinda would quite literally faint if you told her she’d get to teach alongside Suzi, much less hug her twice a week. little me heals a little more every Tuesday and Thursday morning merely by her sheer presence. it takes all i can do to calm my inner child and not stop my class and go watch hers. 

the other day i saw slide 3 of this post on IG and instantly thought of her - then today i saw that it (of course) was her most recent post. happy birthday to the definition of a wonderful someone who walks around making the world a better place. may you feel celebrated tenfold by all the countless lives you’ve changed and touched through the years. i love you. you really are the purest form of magic. ✨

: On this day in 2017 it was @dancingwiththestars Finals. Forever thankful to my earth angel @juleshough for trusting and taking a chance on me, my skeleton crew, the amazing cast and of course, @justinbaldoni & @amusiol.

Funny story, we found out the piece wasn’t going to be pre taped and instead LIVE about 30 minutes before the show. We had yet to successfully clip Jules in on the right timing to fly & obviously for her safety, the amazing crew wasn’t going to fly her if she wasn’t securely clipped in. Never have I held my breath harder than in that moment on live TV. Luckily, Brandon & Nick were rockstars that night & made sure it happened. Shout out to @tombergeron for letting me dig my nails into your arm. 

So much has changed since then. I have hair, I’m only on oral chemo, not IV. I still live as though any moment could be my last, but I plan a bit more for the future, as I’m about to shatter a major milestone doctors predicted I wouldn’t make it to.💥 A lot of the troupe are now Pros, & @juleshough now hosts. But what hasn’t changed is how hard & fast these dancers work, the injuries they work through, the dedication they have for their craft, & how much commitment a show like this requires from each of them. 

Congrats to all my dear friends on an amazing Semi Finals last night. So much love and admiration for you all. 💜 And to anyone who’s been given an expiration date, peel it off and keep walking forward. 

Much love to all the chronic and/or terminally ill warriors this touched. To know so many of you felt seen for the first time, will always be the greatest gift of all of this.

: from as far back as i can remember i have been hyper aware of this woman’s every microexpression. i know the difference between a right & left eyebrow raise, a sigh, a breath, a shift of her eyes. to this day, i glean by how she intonates the “in” in “MarIN” what level of trouble i might be in … even at 39. 🙈 with all that said, she’s unbelievably even more in tuned with me. that’s always been her superpower. she’s like an MRI machine ; able to scan through to the neurons of your brain & catacombs of your soul, downloading what motivates & drives you - memorizing precisely what buttons to push & knobs to dial to get you to operate at your best at all times. 

she was my dance teacher but she was & is so much more. our relationship has always reached far outside the classroom. she loved me, raised me, & disciplined me like i was hers ; and once she realized what dreams i was chasing, she never let me rest on any crutch. i was allowed no excuse, valid or not. every misstep had a consequence & she never missed a damn thing ! feel grateful to have caught the last train of the old school era where that was all possible. i would never have survived all that life has thrown at me if it was any other way. 

so thank you, Ms. MJ, for selflessly raising a kid that wasn’t yours. for every countless unpaid extra hour you spent on me. the work ethic, drive, professionalism, & discipline you instill in every dancer that passes through you is a legacy to be so proud of. you have changed countless lives besides my own. happy, HAPPY birthday to an incredibly special, giving woman. i hope you feel the love today from all who you’ve poured into. from the ones that say it & even the ones that don’t. thanks for saving my life & doing everything in your power to launch me to my wildest dreams. and thank you for allowing me to do the same with your students for the past 20+ years. i love you to the moon. 🌙 @maryjoscanio1 @mjpaa_tampa

: i just want to thank everyone who took time out of their busy lives to celebrate me (almost) reaching a very big milestone. for those that don’t know, at 31, i was diagnosed with Vascular Ehlers-Danlos. at the time, due to the then predicted survival rates, combined with the size of my aorta, and coupled with the tax of 7 other incurable conditions, i was told i would not survive my 3rd decade. 40 instantly became a number that the ticking clock sound in my head incessantly raced towards. it was so maddening and deafening that most of my 3rd decade was spent in a dizzying battle for survival, nonstop sprinting to beat the clock and make a difference, while desperately trying to slow time down with the people i love most.

through chemo, through ICU’s, through isolation, through a trillion tribulations, surgeries, and close calls, sprinkled with the miraculous contradiction of some of my most wild dreams becoming a reality, it was the faces of so many of the people i got to celebrate with Wednesday night that kept me fighting for another day. all the things i’ve lived through mean nothing without the people i love. 

huge thank you to @jacobflynn @blakepiatczyc @jbae86 for making this night so special. i am the luckiest. thank you. 💜
